high school told the Guardian that Tsarnaev appeared to be a \"very relaxed\" person, in contrast to his brother.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon explosions</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/chechnya\">Chechnya</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/massachusetts\">Massachusetts</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/russia\">Russia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/miriam-elder\">Miriam Elder</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston Marathon explosions") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Chechnya") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Massachusetts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "US crime") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Russia") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Europe") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 13:07:16 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-suspect-dzhokhar-tsarnaev-school") (dc:creator nil "Miriam Elder") (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T13:27:15Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407515475") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon explosions, Boston, Chechnya, Massachusetts, US crime, United States, Russia, World news, Europe") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366376597142/Dzhokhar-Tsarnaev-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AFP/Getty Images") (media:description nil "Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, a suspect in the Boston Marathon bombing who being hunted by police in the suburb of Watertown. Photograph: AFP/Getty Images")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366376603573/Dzhokhar-Tsarnaev-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AFP/Getty Images") (media:description nil "Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, a suspect in the Boston Marathon bombing who is being hunted by police in the suburb of Watertown. Photograph: AFP/Getty Images")))) ("Boston bombing: link to Chechnya, if established, would be unprecedented" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/41887?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-bombing-link-chechnya-unprecedented%3A1896478&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+explosions+%28News%29%2CChechnya%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CMassachusetts+%28News%29%2CUS+news%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CCrime+%28US%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Luke+Harding&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+03%3A10&c8=1896478&c9=Article&c10=Analysis&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Boston+bombing%3A+link+to+Chechnya%2C+if+established%2C+would+be+unprecedented&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+explosions\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">If Chechens perpetrated attack, it would be first outside Russia by militants from former Soviet republic</p><p>If it is established that the bombs in Boston were planted by Chechens, it would mark an unprecedented development: the first time militants from the former Soviet republic have carried out a deadly attack outside Russia.</p><p>In their long, violent struggle against the Kremlin, Chechen radicals have hit soft targets before. In 2010 two female suicide bombers from Dagestan blew up the Moscow metro, killing at least 40 people and injuring 100. A year later another suicide bomber struck Moscow's Domodedovo airport; he killed 37 and wounded 180. There have been murderous attacks including the one on a school in Beslan in 2004, where 334 hostages died, most of them children.</p><p>But the bombing of the Boston Marathon, which police suspect was perpetrated by two Chechen brothers, Dzokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, are something altogether new. It is so far unclear how significant is the trail that appears to lead from the mountains of the North Caucasus – the scene of a simmering ongoing insurgency – to the boulevards and suburban houses of North America.</p><p>After 18 years, two wars, and the loss of hundreds of thousands of civilian lives the conflict in Chechnya and Russia's southern backyard more generally has changed. From 1994 to 1996 Boris Yeltsin fought a war against mainly secular Chechen separatists who wanted – like other ethnic republics after the collapse of the USSR – their own nationalist and constitutional state. In the period 1999-2004 Vladimir Putin – Yeltsin's steely successor – fought a second Chechen war. The aim was to definitively crush Chechen separatism.</p><p>In recent years, however, the Kremlin and its regional proxies have been battling a different kind of enemy. This new generation of insurgents has an explicitly Islamist goal: to create a radical pan-Caucasian emirate ruled by Islamic law, a sort of Afghanistan under the Taliban. The movement's leader, Doku Umarov, unveiled this ambitious vision in 2007. He vowed to liberate not only Russia's Muslim North Caucasus but a large chunk of European Russia.</p><p>Umarov also suggested that devout Muslims should think internationally. His comments, later softened, said: \"Today in Afghanistan, Iraq, Somalia, and Palestine our brothers are fighting. Everyone who attacks Muslims wherever they are are our enemies, common enemies. Our enemy is not Russia only, but everyone who wages war against Islam and Muslims.\"</p><p>This call to global jihad may perhaps offer a motive for an attack inside the US. The new generation of twentysomething rebels is also exploiting a powerful new weapon: the internet. The main Chechen rebel website, kavkazcenter.com, posts reports from the jihadi movement worldwide: from Syria, where Chechen diaspora fighters are battling government forces in Aleppo, from Pakistan, and from Turkey.</p><p>Over in the North Caucausus, meanwhile, the Kremlin is carrying out a brutal and rolling counter-insurgency campaign. Its focus is Dagestan, the neighbouring state to Chechnya, and now a hotbed of violent jihadist rebellion. Three weeks ago Umarov appealed to Chechen fighters abroad to come home to take part in the fight.</p><p>Cerwyn Moore, an expert on the insurgency in southern Russia at Birmingham University, said he was surprised it may have spilled over into the United States. \"It's a marked change. It seems very odd. There have never been attacks like this outside Russia.\" He added: \"You have a group of people who have lived outside Chechnya because of the second Chechen war. This is also an inter-generational thing.\"</p><p>Odd or not, the Boston bombings play perfectly into the Kremlin's hands, ahead of Russia's 2014 Winter Olympics, to be hosted in Sochi, not far from where the current insurgency is raging. It reinforces Putin's claim – first made in 1999 – that his violent methods are justified to quell a ruthless rebellion by terrorists prepared to take innocent lives.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon explosions</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/chechnya\">Chechnya</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/russia\">Russia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/massachusetts\">Massachusetts</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/lukeharding\">Luke Harding</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-bombing-link-chechnya-unprecedented" (20849 20576) old 26 nil nil ((title nil "Boston bombing: link to Chechnya, if established, would be unprecedented") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-bombing-link-chechnya-unprecedented") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/41887?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-bombing-link-chechnya-unprecedented%3A1896478&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+explosions+%28News%29%2CChechnya%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CMassachusetts+%28News%29%2CUS+news%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CCrime+%28US%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Luke+Harding&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+03%3A10&c8=1896478&c9=Article&c10=Analysis&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Boston+bombing%3A+link+to+Chechnya%2C+if+established%2C+would+be+unprecedented&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+explosions\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">If Chechens perpetrated attack, it would be first outside Russia by militants from former Soviet republic</p><p>If it is established that the bombs in Boston were planted by Chechens, it would mark an unprecedented development: the first time militants from the former Soviet republic have carried out a deadly attack outside Russia.</p><p>In their long, violent struggle against the Kremlin, Chechen radicals have hit soft targets before. In 2010 two female suicide bombers from Dagestan blew up the Moscow metro, killing at least 40 people and injuring 100. A year later another suicide bomber struck Moscow's Domodedovo airport; he killed 37 and wounded 180. There have been murderous attacks including the one on a school in Beslan in 2004, where 334 hostages died, most of them children.</p><p>But the bombing of the Boston Marathon, which police suspect was perpetrated by two Chechen brothers, Dzokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, are something altogether new. It is so far unclear how significant is the trail that appears to lead from the mountains of the North Caucasus – the scene of a simmering ongoing insurgency – to the boulevards and suburban houses of North America.</p><p>After 18 years, two wars, and the loss of hundreds of thousands of civilian lives the conflict in Chechnya and Russia's southern backyard more generally has changed. From 1994 to 1996 Boris Yeltsin fought a war against mainly secular Chechen separatists who wanted – like other ethnic republics after the collapse of the USSR – their own nationalist and constitutional state. In the period 1999-2004 Vladimir Putin – Yeltsin's steely successor – fought a second Chechen war. The aim was to definitively crush Chechen separatism.</p><p>In recent years, however, the Kremlin and its regional proxies have been battling a different kind of enemy. This new generation of insurgents has an explicitly Islamist goal: to create a radical pan-Caucasian emirate ruled by Islamic law, a sort of Afghanistan under the Taliban. The movement's leader, Doku Umarov, unveiled this ambitious vision in 2007. He vowed to liberate not only Russia's Muslim North Caucasus but a large chunk of European Russia.</p><p>Umarov also suggested that devout Muslims should think internationally. His comments, later softened, said: \"Today in Afghanistan, Iraq, Somalia, and Palestine our brothers are fighting. Everyone who attacks Muslims wherever they are are our enemies, common enemies. Our enemy is not Russia only, but everyone who wages war against Islam and Muslims.\"</p><p>This call to global jihad may perhaps offer a motive for an attack inside the US. The new generation of twentysomething rebels is also exploiting a powerful new weapon: the internet. The main Chechen rebel website, kavkazcenter.com, posts reports from the jihadi movement worldwide: from Syria, where Chechen diaspora fighters are battling government forces in Aleppo, from Pakistan, and from Turkey.</p><p>Over in the North Caucausus, meanwhile, the Kremlin is carrying out a brutal and rolling counter-insurgency campaign. Its focus is Dagestan, the neighbouring state to Chechnya, and now a hotbed of violent jihadist rebellion. Three weeks ago Umarov appealed to Chechen fighters abroad to come home to take part in the fight.</p><p>Cerwyn Moore, an expert on the insurgency in southern Russia at Birmingham University, said he was surprised it may have spilled over into the United States. \"It's a marked change. It seems very odd. There have never been attacks like this outside Russia.\" He added: \"You have a group of people who have lived outside Chechnya because of the second Chechen war. This is also an inter-generational thing.\"</p><p>Odd or not, the Boston bombings play perfectly into the Kremlin's hands, ahead of Russia's 2014 Winter Olympics, to be hosted in Sochi, not far from where the current insurgency is raging. It reinforces Putin's claim – first made in 1999 – that his violent methods are justified to quell a ruthless rebellion by terrorists prepared to take innocent lives.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon explosions</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/chechnya\">Chechnya</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/russia\">Russia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/massachusetts\">Massachusetts</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/lukeharding\">Luke Harding</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston Marathon explosions") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Chechnya") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Russia") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Massachusetts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Europe") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "US crime") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Analysis") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 14:10:40 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-bombing-link-chechnya-unprecedented") (dc:creator nil "Luke Harding") (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T14:10:40Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407519257") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon explosions, Chechnya, Russia, Boston, Massachusetts, United States, Europe, World news, US crime") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366379498570/Tamerlan-and-Dzokhar-Tsar-004.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AP") (media:description nil "Tamerlan and Dzokhar Tsarnaev, two Chechen brothers suspected of being behind the Boston Marathon bombing. Photograph: AP")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366379504563/Tamerlan-and-Dzokhar-Tsar-009.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AP") (media:description nil "Tamerlan and Dzokhar Tsarnaev, who are suspected by police of being behind the Boston Marathon bombing. Photograph: AP")))) ("MIT police officer killed in shooting named as Sean Collier, 26" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/50992?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed%3A1896607&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CMIT+Massachusetts+Institute+of+Technology%2CWorld+news%2CUS+news%2CCrime+%28US%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Amanda+Holpuch&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+04%3A45&c8=1896607&c9=Article&c10=&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=US&c65=MIT+police+officer+killed+in+shooting+named+as+Sean+Collier%2C+26&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Authorities said Collier, who had worked on the MIT police force for about a year, was shot multiple times in his car on Thursday<br /><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-mit-police-dead-watertown\">Follow the latest updates in our Boston live blog</a></p><p>An officer with the Massechusetts Institute of Technology police, Sean Collier, 26, was identified as the victim of a shooting at the university amid a manhunt for the Boston bombing suspects.</p><p>The Middlesex district attorney's office said Collier was shot multiple times in his car on Thursday night. He was pronounced dead at Massachusetts General Hospital.</p><p>\"Sean was one of these guys who really looked at police work as a calling,\" <a href=\"http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2013/victim-identified-as-sean-collier-0419.html\">MIT police chief John DiFava said in a statement</a>. \"He was born to be a police officer.\"</p><p>Collier had served on the MIT police force since 9 January 2012. He was also a member of the school's Outing Club, which organizes outdoor activities for the university community. \"In a very short period of time, it was remarkable how engaged he was with students, particularly graduate students,\" DiFava said.</p><p>Previously, Collier was a civilian employee at the Somerville police department, just north of Boston. He was raised in the north-eastern Massachusetts city of Wilmington, and was single.</p><p>The shooting took place at about 10.30pm. Shortly after, police received reports of an armed car-jacking on the MIT campus in Cambridge.</p><p>In a statement released Friday, MIT said it was \"heartbroken\" by the news. \"Our thoughts are now with the family,\" MIT said. The school cancelled classes, and employees were urged not to come to campus. The school dedicated its website to the officer on Friday – the homepage is now mainly black and includes a large image of the MIT police badge. </p><p>Isabel Ruiz, the MIT executive vice-president and treasurer, and chancellor Eric Grimson, sent a letter to members of the MIT community. It read: \"While the circumstances around the officer's death remain the subject of an active investigation, what is certain is that the officer gave his life to defend the peace of our campus. His sacrifice will never be forgotten by the Institute. We are thinking now of his family, and our hearts are heavy.\"</p><p>Collier was a member of the WAKA Kickball league of greater Boston. <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/WAKAKickballBoston/posts/474325819300454\">The league said in a statement</a> it was heartbroken by the loss of Collier. \"Many of us knew Sean as a kickballer, who played on Sunday afternoons with his team Kickhopopotamus. Our thoughts and prayers go out him, his family, friend, teammates, and those who knew him.\"</p><p>Collier received a criminal justice degree from Salem State university in 2009 and graduated with honors. <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=497716476944387&id=118242334891805\">The school said</a>: \"Our thoughts and sympathy go out to Sean's family as well as all those affected by the recent tragic events in Boston.\"</p><p>A Boston metro transit officer was injured in a separate incident connected to the search for the bombing suspects on Thursday night. The officer, Richard H Donahue Jr, 33, underwent surgery on Friday morning.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/mit-massachusetts-institute-of-technology\">MIT - Massachusetts Institute of Technology</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/amanda-holpuch\">Amanda Holpuch</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/mit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed" (20849 26247) old 25 nil nil ((title nil "MIT police officer killed in shooting named as Sean Collier, 26") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/mit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/50992?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed%3A1896607&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CMIT+Massachusetts+Institute+of+Technology%2CWorld+news%2CUS+news%2CCrime+%28US%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Amanda+Holpuch&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+04%3A45&c8=1896607&c9=Article&c10=&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=US&c65=MIT+po