scape nearby battlefields.</p><p>\"This is the most brutal [conflict], even with very brutal conflicts elsewhere,\" said Guterres. \"If one looks at the impact on the population, or the percentage of the total population in need, I have no doubt that since the end of the cold war it is the worst. And it will become even worse still if there is no solution.</p><p>\"My belief is that if we take all of these elements, then this is the most dramatic humanitarian crisis that we have ever faced. Then if we look at the geopolitical implications, I have no doubt that this is the most serious that we have ever dealt with.\"</p><p>Lebanon and Iraq are increasingly unable to deal with the Syrian spillover, which is disturbing already fraught sectarian power bases and straining meagre resources during an economic downturn brought on by the crisis.</p><p>\"There is a real threat to Lebanon and Iraq,\" said Guterres. \"Jordan is under serious economic stress. We have the Palestinian/Israeli question and the fact that the Syrian army has withdrawn from the Golan Heights. In the context of the Sunni-Shia divide, all the key actors are involved.</p><p>\"Even compared to Afghanistan, the geopolitical implications and the threat to global stability are profound. It's the most dangerous of all crises.\"</p><p>In an address to the United Nations security council on Thursday, Guterres said there had \"not been an inch of progress towards a political solution\".</p><p>Expanding on that to the Guardian, he said: \"It is of enormous frustration that we have come to such a situation in global governance that nobody can address it.\"</p><p>Diplomacy on Syria has failed to bridge a yawning divide in views on what has fuelled the crisis and how best to deal with it. Russia and China, two permanent members of the security council, have blocked moves towards more robust support of the opposition in Syria. The US and Europe have attempted to impose ever-tougher sanctions on the Assad regime, but have baulked at arming the opposition because of concerns about the influence of al-Qaida groups.</p><p>\"I lived in a bi-polar world,\" said Guterres. \"Until the war in Iraq, I witnessed a unipolar world with one single superpower. Now we are in a clearly established multi-polar world. New actors have emerged – the Brics: China, Russia, Brazil, India. There is no longer a clear set of power relations. There is no way to bring about consensus among global players, or to bring about  common action. There is no capacity to produce any solution.\"</p><p>UN appeals for aid to Syria remain desperately under-funded with some agencies, including Unicef, reporting a shortfall of more than 70%. The crisis was eased somewhat on Thursday when Kuwait transferred $300m to the UN for Syria relief. \"[It] will be distributed across all of our institutions,\" said Guterres. The Kuwaitis are the only country of the Gulf that has honoured its promise through the multilateral aid organisations.</p><p>\"We can now put some money up front in Syria, but we are all in big trouble. Most of the western countries have huge budget difficulties. Moving towards 3 million refugees, there is no way that this can be dealt with.</p><p>\"The system is at breaking point. There is limited capacity to take many more. Where are the people going to flee? Into the sea?\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/syria\">Syria</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/unitednations\">United Nations</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/refugees\">Refugees</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/arab-and-middle-east-protests\">Arab and Middle East unrest</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/middleeast\">Middle East and North Africa</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/aid\">Aid</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/martin-chulov\">Martin Chulov</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Syria") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United Nations") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Refugees") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Arab and Middle East unrest") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Middle East and North Africa") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Aid") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Global development") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 12:43:44 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/half-syrian-population-aid-year") (dc:creator nil "Martin Chulov") (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T13:23:19Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407513208") (media:keywords nil "Syria, United Nations, Refugees, Arab and Middle East unrest, Middle East and North Africa, World news, Aid, Global development") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366375290493/Antonio-Guterres-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Junior Kannah/AFP/Getty Images") (media:description nil "The UN high commissioner for refugees, António Guterres, said there had been 'not been an inch of progress towards a political solution' on Syria. Photograph: Junior Kannah/AFP/Getty Images")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366375297256/Antonio-Guterres-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Junior Kannah/AFP/Getty Images") (media:description nil "UN high commissioner António Guterres, said there had 'not been an inch of progress towards a political solution' on Syria. Photograph: Junior Kannah/AFP/Getty Images")))) ("George Osborne to challenge proposed financial transaction tax in court" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/74215?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Auk-legal-challenge-financial-transaction-tax%3A1896702&ch=Law&c3=Guardian&c4=European+court+of+justice%2CLaw%2CEuropean+commission+EC+%28News%29%2CEuropean+Union+EU+%28News%29%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CGeorge+Osborne%2CPolitics%2CTobin+tax%2CEconomics+%28Business%29%2CBanking+%28Business+sector%29%2CFinancial+crisis+%28Business%29%2CFinancial+sector+%28business%29%2CBusiness&c5=Unclassified%2CCredit+Crunch%2CBusiness+Markets%2CPolicy+Society%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBudget%2CInvestments+%26+Savings&c6=Larry+Elliott&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+06%3A01&c8=1896702&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=George+Osborne+to+challenge+proposed+financial+transaction+tax+in+court&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FLaw%2FCourt+of+justice+of+the+European+Union\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Chancellor appeals to European court of justice over plan for worldwide euro levy put forward by 11 EU countries</p><p>Britain is mounting a legal challenge to plans by 11 European nations to adopt a new financial transactions tax amid concerns that the plan will affect banks and institutions in countries outside the scheme.</p><p>The scheme, also known as a Tobin tax, would put a levy on all euro transactions anywhere in the world. But hopes for it suffered a setback when George Osborne said in Washington that the UK was taking the case to the European court of justice (ECJ).</p><p>\"I am not against financial transaction taxes in principle,\" the chancellor said, noting that the UK put stamp duty on shares. \"But I am concerned about the extra-territorial aspects of the European commission's proposals.\"</p><p>Earlier this year 11 countries – Germany, France, Spain, Italy, Belgium, Portugal, Greece, Austria, Slovakia, Slovenia and Estonia – said they had formed a \"coalition of the willing\" that would allow them to forge ahead with the new tax despite the misgivings of other member states.</p><p>Despite opting out of the scheme, Britain and other non-participating members had until Thursday to launch a legal challenge to the specific proposals for the levy drafted in Brussels. Osborne confirmed this had been done, but said Britain's concerns were shared by a number of other countries including the US. The chancellor has also expressed his concerns to the German finance minister Wolfgang Schäuble.</p><p>Britain's objections concern the scope of the tax. Treasury sources said under the current plans it would be levied on a trade in a euro-denominated financial instrument conducted in Singapore by two American banks, for instance.</p><p>The City has also sought clarification on how the levy would affect euro trades completed in London between banks from countries not in the scheme, and from UK subsidiaries of banks in participating countries.</p><p>Osborne believes the tax will damage an already weak eurozone economy and be costly for savers and pensioners because the costs will be passed on.</p><p>It is thought the ECJ will take up to two years to consider the UK's case, but the Treasury believes the legislative process to put the tax into force will take longer. Britain believes its objections can be met while the legislation is being passed and sees the court case as an insurance policy.</p><p>Supporters of the financial transaction tax criticised Osborne's decision. Owen Tudor, spokesman for the <a href=\"http://robinhoodtax.org.uk/\" title=\"\">Robin Hood Tax campaign</a>, said: \"This isn't about defending British interests against Europe – it's about defending one rather rich square mile against the wishes of people in Britain and across Europe.</p><p>\"Not content with letting our banks off scot-free, Osborne now wants to prevent European countries from making their financial sectors pay to repair the damage caused by the crisis.</p><p>\"Resorting to lawyers is the last refuge of a chancellor who has lost the argument.</p><p>\"Not only is this morally wrong, it is breathtakingly hypocritical – the UK's own £3bn stamp duty on shares is collected wherever UK shares are traded and regardless of who is trading them.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/european-court-of-justice\">Court of justice of the European Union</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/european-commission\">European commission</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/eu\">European Union</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/georgeosborne\">George Osborne</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/tobin-tax\">Tobin tax</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/economics\">Economics</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/banking\">Banking</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-crisis\">Financial crisis</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-sector\">Financial sector</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/larryelliott\">Larry Elliott</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/19/uk-legal-challenge-financial-transaction-tax" (20849 30799) old 24 nil nil ((title nil "George Osborne to challenge proposed financial transaction tax in court") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/19/uk-legal-challenge-financial-transaction-tax") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/74215?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Auk-legal-challenge-financial-transaction-tax%3A1896702&ch=Law&c3=Guardian&c4=European+court+of+justice%2CLaw%2CEuropean+commission+EC+%28News%29%2CEuropean+Union+EU+%28News%29%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CGeorge+Osborne%2CPolitics%2CTobin+tax%2CEconomics+%28Business%29%2CBanking+%28Business+sector%29%2CFinancial+crisis+%28Business%29%2CFinancial+sector+%28business%29%2CBusiness&c5=Unclassified%2CCredit+Crunch%2CBusiness+Markets%2CPolicy+Society%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBudget%2CInvestments+%26+Savings&c6=Larry+Elliott&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+06%3A01&c8=1896702&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=George+Osborne+to+challenge+proposed+financial+transaction+tax+in+court&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FLaw%2FCourt+of+justice+of+the+European+Union\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Chancellor appeals to European court of justice over plan for worldwide euro levy put forward by 11 EU countries</p><p>Britain is mounting a legal challenge to plans by 11 European nations to adopt a new financial transactions tax amid concerns that the plan will affect banks and institutions in countries outside the scheme.</p><p>The scheme, also known as a Tobin tax, would put a levy on all euro transactions anywhere in the world. But hopes for it suffered a setback when George Osborne said in Washington that the UK was taking the case to the European court of justice (ECJ).</p><p>\"I am not against financial transaction taxes in principle,\" the chancellor said, noting that the UK put stamp duty on shares. \"But I am concerned about the extra-territorial aspects of the European commission's proposals.\"</p><p>Earlier this year 11 countries – Germany, France, Spain, Italy, Belgium, Portugal, Greece, Austria, Slovakia, Slovenia and Estonia – said they had formed a \"coalition of the willing\" that would allow them to forge ahead with the new tax despite the misgivings of other member states.</p><p>Despite opting out of the scheme, Britain and other non-participating members had until Thursday to launch a legal challenge to the specific proposals for the levy drafted in Brussels. Osborne confirmed this had been done, but said Britain's concerns were shared by a number of other countries including the US. The chancellor has also expressed his concerns to the German finance minister Wolfgang Schäuble.</p><p>Britain's objections concern the scope of the tax. Treasury sources said under the current plans it would be levied on a trade in a euro-denominated financial instrument conducted in Singapore by two American banks, for instance.</p><p>The City has also sought clarification on how the levy would affect euro trades completed in London between banks from countries not in the scheme, and from UK subsidiaries of banks in participating countries.</p><p>Osborne believes the tax will damage an already weak eurozone economy and be costly for savers and pensioners because the costs will be passed on.</p><p>It is thought the ECJ will take up to two years to consider the UK's case, but the Treasury believes the legislative process to put the tax into force will take longer. Britain believes its objections can be met while the legislation is being passed and sees the court case as an insurance policy.</p><p>Supporters of the financial transaction tax criticised Osborne's decision. Owen Tudor, spokesman for the <a href=\"http://robinhoodtax.org.uk/\" title=\"\">Robin Hood Tax campaign</a>, said: \"This isn't about defending British interests against Europe – it's about defending one rather rich square mile against the wishes of people in Britain and across Europe.</p><p>\"Not content with letting our banks off scot-free, Osborne now wants to prevent European countries from making their financial sectors pay to repair the damage caused by the crisis.</p><p>\"Resorting to lawyers is the last refuge of a chancellor who has lost the argument.</p><p>\"Not only is this morally wrong, it is breathtakingly hypocritical – the UK's own £3bn stamp duty on shares is collected wherever UK shares are traded and regardless of who is trading them.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/european-court-of-justice\">Court of justice of the European Union</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/european-commission\">European commission</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/eu\">European Union</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/georgeosborne\">George Osborne</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/tobin-tax\">Tobin tax</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/economics\">Economics</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/banking\">Banking</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-crisis\">Financial crisis</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-sector\">Financial sector</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/larryelliott\">Larry Elliott</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Court of justice of the European Union") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Law") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "European commission") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "European Union") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Europe") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "George Osborne") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Politics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Tobin tax") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Economics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Banking") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Financial crisis") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Financial sector") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Business") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 17:01:03 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/19/uk-legal-challenge-financial-transaction-tax") (dc:creator nil "Larry Elliott") (dc:subject nil "Law") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T17:01:03Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407535617") (media:keywords nil "Court of justice of the European Union, Law, European commission, European Union, Europe, World news, George Osborne, Politics, Tobin tax, Economics, Banking, Financial crisis, Financial sector, Business") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/cartoons/2013/4/19/1366390643118/U.S.-Treasury-Secretary-J-004.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Yuri Gripas/Reuters") (media:description nil "George Osborne with Jack Lew, the US treasury secretary, in Washington. Photograph: Yuri Gripas/Reuters")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/cartoons/2013/4/19/1366390649461/U.S.-Treasury-Secretary-J-009.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Yuri Gripas/Reuters") (media:description nil "George Osborne with Jack Lew, the US treasury secretary, in Washington. Photograph: Yuri Gripas/Reuters")))) ("Tatyana McFadden dedicates London Marathon title bid to Boston victims" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/53355?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-london-marathon-tatyana-mcfadden%3A1896620&ch=Sport&c3=Guardian&c4=London+Marathon%2CBoston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CAthletics%2CSport&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2COutdoor+and+Active&c6=James+Riach&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A39&c8=1896620&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Tatyana+McFadden+dedicates+London+Marathon+title+bid+to+Boston+victims&c66=Sport&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FSport%2FSport%2FLondon+Marathon\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">McFadden won Boston's women's wheelchair race just before two bombs turned the finish area into a scene of carnage</p><p>\"It was so surreal, you could just see the blank look on people's faces,\" says Tatyana McFadden of the scenes after the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/16/boston-marathon-bloody-chaos\" title=\"\">two bomb blasts at the Boston Marathon</a> that overshadowed her victory in the women's wheelchair race. McFadden will compete in the London equivalent on Sunday and try to secure a unique double triumph.  But more pertinently, she will be racing for those who lost their lives last Monday.</p><p>\"I'm racing for the people in Boston, I'm dedicating the race to them,\" she says. \"People have been asking me if I'm going to race on Sunday, I'm like 'yes'. I'm not going to let what happened in Boston win, it's about continuing to live your life.</p><p>\"When I run in London I will carry those people in my hearts, the people who were killed or injured. There's always going to be a few bad people in the world but the majority are good.\"</p><p>McFadden, 23, an adopted American who was born in Leningrad, won three golds at London 2012 although she was denied in the marathon when a tyre punctured. Her victory in Boston should be remembered as another career highlight but instead the events that followed almost made the win feel like an irrelevance.</p><p>\"It was just a normal day,\" she says. \"When I crossed the finish line I couldn't believe that I was first in Boston and that I had won. I then went into a hotel at the finish line to do media and drug testing before heading back to my hotel. After showering I came out and my whole family and my team-mate Amanda were there, jaws dropped and watching TV. We were watching the replay over and over.</p><p>\"I was worried about other people, the marathon community is separate from track and you really get to know people. To see what happened – your eyes start to fill up with tears. But the medical staff reacted so quickly and people who were on the course ran to the hospital to donate blood.\"</p><p>Born with an underdeveloped spinal chord resulting in paralysis below the waist, McFadden is among 24 wheelchair athletes who have made the trip from Boston to compete in London.</p><p>Nicknamed \"the beast\" at university because of her weightlifting prowess, she walked on her hands for six years before being adopted by an American family in Baltimore. The 23-year-old will have a black ribbon pinned to her top on Sunday and admits her thoughts during the race will drift back to Boston.</p><p>\"I'm going to have it in the back of my mind,\" McFadden says. \"But I'm not nervous about competing, the security has been really good. There were people who picked us up right after we got off the plane.</p><p>\"People came together in Boston. It was about strangers helping strangers and people coming together as a community to help each other out. It didn't tear people apart – it brought people together and that was what mattered the most.</p><p>\"As an elite athlete with a disability, I'm a model for anybody – a person newly disabled or anybody. It's my job as an athlete to represent them and I hope to inspire people.\"</p><p>Boston also holds a special place in the heart of Geoffrey Mutai, the course record-holder for able-bodied men with a time of 2hr 3min 2sec set in 2011, the fastest marathon time despite it not being recognised by the International Association of Athletics Federations owing to the layout of Boston's race.</p><p>Mutai will compete in the \"best elite men's field ever\" on Sunday, but the Kenyan will also be thinking about Monday's attacks. \"It was painful to see,\" he said. \"It's a special place and I know the city well. In sport for something to happen like that … you just think 'what did this person want?' People were running, people were tired, you should be there cheering with family and friends. I say to Boston we are very sorry, we are feeling so sad but we are together.</p><p>\"When you are running you are only focusing on your event, as an athlete you can't have any security concerns about terrorists. You must have a free mind and focus on your race. For things to happen in a competition like that is so sad, we must pray to god. We have been told the security will be tight.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/london-marathon\">London Marathon</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/athletics\">Athletics</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/james-riach\">James Riach</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/apr/19/boston-london-marathon-tatyana-mcfadden" (20849 29533) old 27 nil nil ((title nil "Tatyana McFadden dedicates London Marathon title bid to Boston victims") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/apr/19/boston-london-marathon-tatyana-mcfadden") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/53355?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-london-marathon-tatyana-mcfadden%3A1896620&ch=Sport&c3=Guardian&c4=London+Marathon%2CBoston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CAthletics%2CSport&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2COutdoor+and+Active&c6=James+Riach&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A39&c8=1896620&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Tatyana+McFadden+dedicates+London+Marathon+title+bid+to+Boston+victims&c66=Sport&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FSport%2FSport%2FLondon+Marathon\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">McFadden won Boston's women's wheelchair race just before two bombs turned the finish 