lf in and ask for forgiveness, from the victims, from the injured, and from those who left. Ask forgiveness from these people.\"</p><p>We're not requiring forgiveness in this family. He put a shame on our family. He put a shame on the entire Chechen ethnicity, because everyone now names [Chechen], they play with that word Chechen. So they put that shame on the entire ethnicity. I would say, \"Turn yourself in, and put yourself in the discretion of those who are here.\"</p><p>[…] Again, with the families of those who suffered, we're sharing them their grief. I'm ready just to meet with them, I'm ready to bend in front of them, to kneel in front of them, seeking forgiveness.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/chechnya\">Chechnya</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/russia\">Russia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/dzhokhar-tsarnaev\">Dzhokhar Tsarnaev</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/terrorism\">Global terrorism</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/tamerlan-tsarnaev\">Tamerlan Tsarnaev</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/ruslan-tsarni\">Ruslan Tsarni</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston Marathon bombing") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Chechnya") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Russia") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Dzhokhar Tsarnaev") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Global terrorism") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Tamerlan Tsarnaev") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Comment") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 17:51:39 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/dzhokhar-tsarnaev-ruslan-tsarni-forgiveness") (dc:creator nil "Ruslan Tsarni") (dc:subject nil "Comment is free") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T17:52:21Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407540759") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon bombing, Chechnya, Russia, Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, United States, World news, Global terrorism, Tamerlan Tsarnaev") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366393562714/ruslantsarni_140x84.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "guardian.co.uk") (media:description nil "Screengrab of Ruslan Tsarni")))) ("Catalan human tower dazzles crowd in London" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91252?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Acatalan-human-tower-crowd-london%3A1896722&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Catalonia+%28News%29%2CLondon+%28News%29%2CUK+news%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CHeritage+%28Culture%29%2CCulture&c5=Society+Weekly%2CUnclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Sam+Jones&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+06%3A44&c8=1896722&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Catalan+human+tower+dazzles+crowd+in+London&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FCatalonia\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">170 castellers, aged six to 75, clamber on top of each other as part of weekend of festivities to mark St George's Day</p><p>To the bemusement of lunchtime joggers, the fascination of Thames-side tourists and the delight of the odd homesick Mediterranean heart, London sprouted yet another tower on Friday afternoon.</p><p>But the structure that sprang up at the foot of City Hall, not far from Tower Bridge and the Tower of London, was built not from stone and mortar nor steel and glass but forged rather from Catalan flesh and bone.</p><p>For almost 300 years, the people of <a href=\"www.guardian.co.uk/world/catalonia\" title=\"\">Catalonia</a> have been congregating in plaças to try to build the highest possible human tower through a peculiar combination of balance, strength and outright fearlessness.</p><p>Though a familiar sight in their homeland, the <a href=\"http://www.castellersdevilafranca.cat/\" title=\"\">Castellers de Vilafranca</a> proved enough of a novelty in the capital to draw a crowd who watched – many holding their breath – as the Catalans clambered on top of each other to construct their six-level castells.</p><p>The 170 castellers, aged from six to 75, are in London to show off their skills and to help celebrate St George's Day; the dragon-slayer is also the patron saint of Catalonia.</p><p>On Saturday afternoon they will be performing on Clapham Common while Sunday will find them by the Millennium Bridge on Bankside and at Borough Market, which will be hosting Sant Jordi celebrations.</p><p>Miquel Ferret, a civil servant from Vilafranca and committed casteller, said the tradition – <a href=\"http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/RL/00364\" title=\"\">judged by Unesco to form part of the \"intangible cultural heritage of humanity\"</a> – lay at the very heart of the Catalan identity.</p><p>\"Building towers is a way of working as a team where class doesn't matter,\" he said. \"We've got the mayor, we've got priests, we've got lawyers and doctors and we've got farm-workers and unemployed people.\"</p><p>For Catalans, he added, castells are both an expression and a celebration of community.</p><p>\"Some people sing or play sports, but building towers is a mix of lots of things: it's half-culture and half-sport but all bound up with our traditions and our identity as a people,\" he added. \"It's a bit of everything.\"</p><p>Despite insisting that anyone could be a casteller – \"whether you're strong, very heavy, thin, tall, or short, everyone has a place\" – Ferret conceded that certain attributes were desirable: \"You need strength, balance, bravery and sense – you have to know where your limits are.\"</p><p>All those qualities – and several more – were evident in the diminutive figure of María Mhaf, an eight-year-old from Vilafranca who has been scaling the heights of the castells from more than a year.</p><p>Emerging, crash-helmeted, from the base of a dismantled castell to fetch her gumshield from her proud father, María explained that she had wanted to be a casteller from the age of five.</p><p>In common with many focused athletes, she was laconic when discussing her motivation.</p><p>\"When I'm at the top,\" she said, \"I feel peaceful.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/catalonia\">Catalonia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/london\">London</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/heritage\">Heritage</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/samjones\">Sam Jones</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/catalan-human-tower-crowd-london" (20849 33386) old 16 nil nil ((title nil "Catalan human tower dazzles crowd in London") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/catalan-human-tower-crowd-london") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91252?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Acatalan-human-tower-crowd-london%3A1896722&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Catalonia+%28News%29%2CLondon+%28News%29%2CUK+news%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CHeritage+%28Culture%29%2CCulture&c5=Society+Weekly%2CUnclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Sam+Jones&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+06%3A44&c8=1896722&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Catalan+human+tower+dazzles+crowd+in+London&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FCatalonia\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">170 castellers, aged six to 75, clamber on top of each other as part of weekend of festivities to mark St George's Day</p><p>To the bemusement of lunchtime joggers, the fascination of Thames-side tourists and the delight of the odd homesick Mediterranean heart, London sprouted yet another tower on Friday afternoon.</p><p>But the structure that sprang up at the foot of City Hall, not far from Tower Bridge and the Tower of London, was built not from stone and mortar nor steel and glass but forged rather from Catalan flesh and bone.</p><p>For almost 300 years, the people of <a href=\"www.guardian.co.uk/world/catalonia\" title=\"\">Catalonia</a> have been congregating in plaças to try to build the highest possible human tower through a peculiar combination of balance, strength and outright fearlessness.</p><p>Though a familiar sight in their homeland, the