04-19T17:43:14Z") (dc:type nil "Video") (dc:identifier nil "407538310") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon bombing, Boston, Massachusetts, Gun crime, United States, World news, Tamerlan Tsarnaev, Dzhokhar Tsarnaev") (media:group nil (media:content ((fileSize . "43679578") (type . "video/mp4") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/truemainwebsite/2013/4/19mainwebsite/2013/4/19/130419BostonUncle-16x9.mp4"))) (media:content ((fileSize . "164059966") (type . "video/mp4:720") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/4/19/130419BostonUncle-720.mp4"))) (media:content ((fileSize . "38687545") (type . "video/3gpp:small") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/4/19/130419BostonUncle_3gpSml16x9.3gp"))) (media:content ((fileSize . "71773498") (type . "video/3gpp:large") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/4/19/130419BostonUncle_3gpLg16x9.3gp"))) (media:content ((type . "video/m3u8") (url . "http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/4/19/130419BostonUncle/130419BostonUncle.m3u8")))) (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2013/4/19/1366391293278/Uncle-Of-Boston-Bombers-006.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Allison Shelley/Getty Images") (media:description nil "Uncle Of Boston Bombers Photograph: Allison Shelley/Getty Images")))) ("London Marathon runners say they run in solidarity with Boston" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/32591?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Alondon-marathon-runners-solidarity-boston%3A1896717&ch=Sport&c3=Guardian&c4=London+Marathon%2CBoston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CMassachusetts+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CWorld+news%2CUS+news%2CAthletics%2CSport%2CCrime+%28US%29%2CLondon+%28News%29%2CUK+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2COutdoor+and+Active&c6=Owen+Gibson&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+06%3A34&c8=1896717&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=London+Marathon+runners+say+they+run+in+solidarity+with+Boston&c66=Sport&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FSport%2FSport%2FLondon+Marathon\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Many of those registering for Sunday's event say they will run for those killed and injured by bombs at the finish line in the US</p><p>In addition to the usual last minute nerves, the ritual loading of carbohydrates at the pasta party and the sensory overload of competing advice, those queuing to pick up their London Marathon numbers agreed that events in Boston this week had given them another reason to race.</p><p>As police confirmed that there would be 40% more officers on duty in the wake of Monday's bombs and Westminster Council removed all litter bins from the route as a security measure, those taking part said their sense of sadness and solidarity with competitors in Boston would help inspire them to finish the 26.2 mile course alongside 36,000 others.</p><p>Many of those registering at the cavernous London Marathon Expo at the ExCel conference centre, which is on the other side of the Thames from where they will gather on Sunday at the start line, had their own, deeply personal reasons for wanting to complete in the race.</p><p>Some were running in the memory of a deceased friend or relative, others to raise money for charity and others simply to beat their target time.</p><p>But as they picked up the black ribbons that they will wear on their running vests alongside their race number, most agreed that they would also be running for those who were killed and injured by the bombs that exploded close to the finish line in Boston at a time when the elite participants were back in their hotel and those still running were recreational competitors like them.</p><p>All said they had been left shaken by the blasts and some said they initially considered the security implications for London. But almost all agreed that London organisers were right to immediately signal their determination not to cancel.</p><p>In the wake of the Boston bombs, much was made of the sense of global kinship felt by marathon runners, and it was much in evidence in the otherwise sterile surroundings of ExCel. Runners have come from around the world to compete in London just as hundreds from Great Britain and Ireland had taken part in Boston.</p><p>\"I am running the marathon in honour of my dad who passed away three years ago and was really into his sport,\" said Kim Butigan, a 24-year-old journalist from Dubrovnik in Croatia. \"I was shaken [after what happened in Boston] and apprehensive about running but we must not let these things affect our everyday lives.\"</p><p>Many of those registering have taken part in other marathons around the world, from Tokyo to Berlin.</p><p>Chris McBeth, a farrier from Colchester who is an experienced marathon runner, was sporting a homemade Boston ribbon in yellow and blue that his partner Zoe had begun selling on Facebook to raise money for the victims of the bombing. In less than 24 hours, she had raised £100. \"I have been applying for six years so this is a really good opportunity. It didn't give me second thoughts at all. It was just so tragically moving. We had just come back from the Brighton marathon, where I was at that point at the finish waiting for Zoe,\" he said.</p><p>\"If anything, it makes you more determined to do it. The running community has been so supportive. All runners everywhere want to show solidarity.\"</p><p>Organisers will hold a 30-second silence before each of the three starts and, in addition to the black ribbons handed to every runner, have also announced that they will donate £2 to the Boston First fund for every finisher.</p><p>Anne Sinagra, who works for the city council in Bordeaux, had travelled to London to run with her sister-in-law Alice Cavender, who also lives in the French city. Both completed their first London marathon last year and are running again for Action Medical Research. \"It was the best day of my life. We crossed the finishing line together holding hands. The crowd was amazing,\" said Sinagra.</p><p>\"I watched the news Monday night and I was very, very sad for the runners and all the families. It's supposed to be a day of joy and sharing. Sunday will be very emotional because all the runners will run for the same cause.\"</p><p>James Wright, who had travelled from Oldham with his wife Della and hopes to complete the race dressed as Little Miss Chatterbox, predicted that crowds would turn out in even greater numbers in light of events in Boston. \"You can't let them stop you. It's two fingers up to anyone who wants to try and stop us.\"</p><p>Typically, a crowd of around half a million throngs the 26.2 mile route that starts in Blackheath in south east London and ends on the Mall, and lends the event its unique atmosphere.</p><p>Among the runners will be Dr Jack Holland, a lecturer in international relations at the University of Surrey and an expert on terrorism and security policy. In a blog written in the aftermath of the bombing, he wrote: \"'Carry on' has been a prominent British response to the events in Massachusetts. And that is not a bad start. So while Boston's 26th mile was dedicated, tragically, to the victims of the Newtown shootings, many running the London Marathon on Sunday will do so with Boston in mind.\"</p><p>The elite runners also insisted that the Boston bombings would not deter them. Mo Farah, who is running the first half of the marathon in preparation for a tilt at the full distance next year, said: \"My support goes out to all the people involved, their families and loved ones. But they would want us to carry on and show our support. Why would you let it stop you?\"</p><p>The sports minister, Hugh Robertson, said the extra security measures and added police numbers were to provide \"reassurance\". \"If we thought there was anything there that should stop people going out onto the streets, we would say so and we would call the whole thing off,\" he said. \"The threat level remains exactly the same as it always was, we've had many marathons here, we've looked at the experience of many, many marathons abroad.\"</p><p><em>Additional reporting: Arjun Kharpal</em></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/london-marathon\">London Marathon</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/massachusetts\">Massachusetts</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/athletics\">Athletics</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/london\">London</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/owengibson\">Owen Gibson</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/apr/19/london-marathon-runners-solidarity-boston" (20849 32797) old 20 nil nil ((title nil "London Marathon runners say they run in solidarity with Boston") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2013/apr/19/london-marathon-runners-solidarity-boston") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/32591?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Alondon-marathon-runners-solidarity-boston%